      <h1>Acknowledgement of Country</h1>
      <div class="post-header__meta">
        <span>We live and work on stolen land.</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        This business was founded on Wadawurrung Country.</p>

      <p>
        We acknowledge the Wadawurrung people as the Traditional Owners and
        custodians of the land on which we operate, and pay our respects to
        their Elders past and present.</p> 

      <p>
        We recognise that sovereignty over this land was never ceded, and
        that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples have practiced
        the work of caring for Country for tens of thousands of years
        before made by multitudes existed. This was, and always will be,
        Aboriginal land.
      </p>
        
      <p>We conduct business throughout Australia and the world, and we acknowledge the Traditional Owners of all the lands on which we operate. We pay our respects to their Elders past and present, and to all First Nations peoples.</p>
     
      <p>
        An Acknowledgement is a small thing. It is
        also not enough on its own. We continue to think about how the way
        we work — who we hire, who we partner with, what we publish, where
        our money goes — can move beyond words.
      </p>

      <h2>About this page</h2>

      <p>This page was written in good faith by the founder of made by multitudes, Matt Smith, an Indigenous Australian descended from the Gubbi Gubbi people.</p>

      <p>
        If you are unsure whose Country you are on, the
        <a href="https://aiatsis.gov.au/explore/map-indigenous-australia" rel="external">AIATSIS Map of Indigenous Australia</a>
        is a starting point. For an authoritative answer, contact the
        relevant local Traditional Owner organisation or land council
        directly.
      </p>
    </div>

  </article>
</Base>
